of various transformers, to be runin parallel, do not   show 
identical values, there will be circulating currents between 
the secondaries (and therefore between primaries also) 
when the secondary terminals are connected in parallel. 
The impedances of transformers is small, so that a small 
percentage voltage difference may be sufficient to circulate 
considerable current and cause additional I7R loss. 
Vvhen secondaries are loaded, the circulating current will 
tendto produce unequal loading conditions. Thus it may 
be impossible to take the full load output from the parallel 
connected groupwithout one of the transformers becoming 
excessively heated. 
Impedance: The currents carried by the two transformers 
are proportional to their ratings: 
*   if their numerical or ohmic impedances are inversely 
 proportional to those ratings, and 
 *   their per unit impedances are identical. 
Adifference inthe quality factor   (i.ethe ratio of reactance 
to   resistance)   of the   per unit   impedance   results in   a 
divergence ofthe phase angle of the currents, sothat one 
transformer willbe working witha higher andthe other with 
a lower power factor than that of the combined output. 
